description._value: Selection of the optimal injection solvent composition for the analysis of cassava extracts with LC-DAD.

Sample preparation. A pooled sample was prepared from freeze dried leaves of 22 plants of cassava grown in vitro. The pooled sample was ground to a fine powder using a freezer mill (Specs Centriprep., Stanmore, UK) and stored at -20C until the time of extraction. Samples were extracted from homogenised powder (10 mg), adding 800 μL of methanol:water (50:50, v:v) and 800 μL of chloroform, vortexing briefly and subsequently mixing for one hour in a Stuart SB3 rotator at 40 rpm (Bibby Scientific Limited, Staffordshire, UK). The samples were then centrifuged for three minutes at 17000 g, and the chloroform phase was collected by carefully pipeting. The chloroform phase of 30 samples prepared in this way was collected in a single receptacle. The pooled extract was divided into 200 μL aliquots which were dried by centrifugal evaporation. Samples were stored dry at -20C prior to resuspending for chromatography.

Samples were resuspended in different solvent mixtures (total volume of 50 μL). A series of samples were prepared using 0 to 100% by vol. of ethyl acetate in acetonitrile in steps of 5%. All solvent combinations were tested in triplicate. When the solvent mixture contained ethyl acetate, the latter was the first to be added to assist solubilisation. The dried pellet was resuspended by vortexing and samples were then centrifuged as before. 40 μL of the clear supernatant were transferred to a 2 mL screw cap glass vial with a 250 μL glass insert. Samples were prepared in random order in batches of 24 and placed in the autosampler at 8C for chromatography.

Chromatography was performed on a Waters Acquity UPLC equipped with an Acquity UPLC BEH C18 column (1.7 μm, 2.1 x 100 mm) at 30 C. Elution was carried out by a gradient of two solvents, A (methanol 50% in water) and B (ethyl acetate 25% in acetonitrile). The gradient started at 30% A, held isocratically for 0.5 minutes followed by a linear ramp to 0.1% of A for 3.5 minutes, and holding for 2 minutes. The column was returned to initial conditions and allowed to equilibrate for 3 minutes, the total run time being 9 minutes.

Elution of isoprenoids was detected with the help of a Waters Acquity UPLC Photodiode Array (PDA) eλ detector. The DAD signal was acquired from 250 to 600 nm (step 1.2 nm) with a resolution of 1.2 nm, at a frequency of 20 points per second.

title._value: Metabolite profiling in LC-DAD using multivariate curve resolution: the alsace package in R
